headline.main: Paid Notice: Deaths  KLAUSNER, ROBERT

lead_paragraph: KLAUSNER--Robert B. Bob, civic leader, political advocate, and philanthropist left us on March 27, after years of failing health. He left behind the love of his life, wife Betty, children Mimi (Kim), Drew and Kathy, their partners, Susan, Susan, and Beni, brother Bill and family, Kampan, Boon Song and Khem, major domo Virginia Ribeiro, brother-in-law Clay Tedeschi, his Miller cousins, grandchildren Guston, Olive, Noah, Max, Emma and Oscar, great- grandchild Theodore and cousin Leslie Steinmetz. Bob was born October 4, 1926 to David and Mickey (Miller) Klausner in Jersey City, NJ. He graduated from Yale and moved to Manhattan when he married Betty in 1950. Bob worked in sales for H. Warshow and Sons, a textile company. The family moved to Santa Barbara, CA in 1973. He was involved in community environmental issues such as offshore oil production, recycling, conservation, and land use. He mentored political reformers and worked to keep government accountable to its citizens. Bob and Betty moved in 1993 to San Francisco, CA, where all their children and grandchildren were then living. He was involved in many projects including community mediation, investigative journalism, and campaign finance reform. Bob Klausner was witty, warm, and a wise old-school gentleman. A memorial service is being planned in San Francisco.

headline.main: Paid Notice: Deaths  ANNS, ARLENE

lead_paragraph:
ANNS--Arlene Eiserman,

of Charlottesville, Virginia, died peacefully at Westminster-Canterbury nursing center on March 28, 2016, with her husband Philip at her side. Arlene was born in Pearl River, New York on June 16, 1928 to Frederick and Ann Eiserman. She graduated from Utah State University with a BS in political science in 1950, and also attended the Wharton School for fundamentals of finance and accounting, as well as the Traphagen School of Design and Hunter College. Arlene became the first woman magazine publisher at McGraw-Hill Companies in New York City, and the first woman to receive the Advertising Representative Award in the medical field. Arlene went on to hold senior publishing appointments with many magazines such as Vice President at Morgan Grampian (a British publishing company), Aviation Week and Space Technology, Esquire, and Post Graduate Medicine and Graduating Engineer. Throughout her distinguished publishing career, Arlene received many awards for her achievements in marketing. On her retirement she was a volunteer member of the Service Corps of Retired Executives (SCORE) in Charlottesville, VA and on the Board of Directors of the National Organization on Disability. Prior to moving into the Westminster-Canterbury Senior Living Center in August 2015, Arlene and her husband Philip of thirty-eight years owned and managed Barnahill Farm in Greene County which received the 2013 Forestry Award for exceptional forestry management. Arlene is survived by her husband Philip, his daughter Jean Anns Fritchley and her husband Ron Jr., by her nephews Mark Eiserman and his wife Sharlene, Eric Eiserman and Chris Eiserman and his wife Jeanene, as well as three grandchildren and five great- grandchildren. She was predeceased by her brother Fred Eiserman. Calling hours will be held Thursday, April 28 from 6:00 until 8:00pm, at Hill & Wood Funeral Home, 201 North First Street, Charlottesville, VA. 22902. Celebration of her life services to follow on Friday, April 29 at 11:00am, St. Paul's Episcopal Church Ivy, 851 Owensville Road, Charlottesville, VA 22901. In lieu of flowers, donations can be made to St. Paul's Church Ivy. Friends may send condolences to her family at www.hillandwood.com

lead_paragraph:
DORIAN--Edward S. Sr.,

of Purchase, NY, founder and former chairman of Dorian Drake International, died on April 20 following a long battle with cancer. He was 92. Born on March 8, 1924 in Orange, NJ, he was the second son of Armenian immigrants who fled Turkey to escape persecution in the early 1900's. After graduating Orange High School in 1942, he served in the U.S. Army in Europe and Japan during WWII. He later attended Seton Hall University, where he majored in business and graduated Magna Cum Laude in 1949. In a rich and varied international business career that followed, he pioneered two industries-export finance and export management - and positively influenced the lives and careers of many people who worked with him. He worked for the Arabian American Oil Company from 1949-1967, during which time he worked for periods in Lebanon, the Netherlands and Saudi Arabia and earned an MBA from NYU. He then served as president of Drake America, a New York-based export management and its affiliate, Export Credit Corporation, from 1967-1974. He left to found Creditcorp International, another export finance company, in 1975, where he worked until 1981, when he started Dorian International, an export management company. The new company, Dorian International, acquired his former company, Drake America, in 1985 and later unified its identity as Dorian Drake International. Based in White Plains, NY, the firm continues today under the leadership of his oldest son, Edward Dorian Jr. An avid golfer, he was a long-time member of Westchester Hills Golf Club in White Plains, NY and later an active member of Westchester Country Club in Rye, NY and Broken Sound Country Club in Boca Raton, FL. He was also a founding member and first elected parish council chairman of St. Gregory Armenian Church of Westchester. A devoted family man, he is survived by his adoring wife Ethel, whom he married in 1951; a daughter Donna; son Edward Jr.; daughter-in- law Andrea; and two grandsons, Nicholas and Kenneth, who were for their grandfather a source of great pride; and a large and loving extended family. He was predeceased by his son Gregory, who died in 1992. Memorial fund details to follow. The family will receive friends at the Graham Funeral Home, Rye, NY on Friday, April 29, from 2-4pm and 7-9pm.

headline.main: Paid Notice: Deaths  LINTON, ROBERT

lead_paragraph:
LINTON--Robert E.

Robert E. Linton, former CEO and Chairman of Drexel Burnham Lambert, Inc., died April 26, 2016 at the age of 90. During the early 1980s, Mr. Linton served as the head of the storied investment banking and securities firm that pioneered the use of high yield (or "junk") bonds. Robert Linton was born in New York City on May 19, 1925 to Helen and Adolph Lichtenstein, a specialist on the New York Stock Exchange. During his senior year at Phillips Exeter Academy, Linton enlisted in the Army, eventually serving in WWII as a navigator and bombardier and achieving the rank of 2nd lieutenant in the Army Air Force. In 1946, Mr. Linton joined Burnham & Co., a small investment bank as the eighth employee, starting as a runner delivering stock certificates around Wall Street. Hard-working and ambitious, Bob attended night school to earn his stock broker's license and later, his commodities broker's license.
